    "en": {
     "title": "Cyrus II, Persian Emperor",
     "blurb": "A world on fire, and the young prince who would found the Achaemenid Empire.",
     "script": "Cyrus the Second, Persian Emperor. This carved relief from Persepolis shows a procession of Persian and Median nobles. Cyrus was born into a world on fire. Between nine hundred and eleven and six hundred and nine BCE, the regional superpower was the Neo-Assyrian empire. They were famous for their viciousness, and dominated the Medes of northwestern Iran and the Babylonians of Southern Mesopotamia. In seven hundred and twenty-two BCE the Assyrians captured the Northern Kingdom of Israel and enslaved them, the so-called lost tribes; and in six hundred and twelve BCE the Assyrians themselves were destroyed by a coalition of their enemies, as the Babylonians united with the Medians and the Scythians to conquer them. The Babylonians then inherited the Kingdom of Judah in Jerusalem. When the Israelites rebelled against their new King, he crushed them, destroying Solomon's Temple around five hundred and eighty-seven BCE. All of this had been foretold. After the Assyrian enslavement of the Northern Kingdom of Israel, the Prophet Nahum foretold Assyria's downfall, saying, in the Book of Nahum, chapter one, verse fourteen: \"You will have no descendants to bear your name. I will destroy the images and idols that are in the temple of your gods. I will prepare your grave, for you are vile.\" His prophecy was fulfilled within decades. But the Babylonians then captured the Southern Kingdom of Judah, and exiled its people, who wept in captivity. As the Psalm records, in Psalm one hundred and thirty-seven, verse one: \"By the rivers of Babylon, there we sat down, yea, we wept, when we remembered Zion.\" Their saviour would not be an Israelite, but a Zoroastrian; and the Bible would call him 'Messiah'. Into this turmoil came Cyrus, born around six hundred to five hundred and ninety BCE. In five hundred and fifty-nine BCE he inherited the kingdom of the small Persian state of Anshan, a vassal of the Medians led by a man who was potentially Cyrus's own grandfather, Astyages. Astyages was said to be a cruel ruler, whose policies bred great disaffection among the Median nobility. Cyrus overthrew him and united the kingdoms of Media and Persia under himself, and in doing so laid the foundation of the great Achaemenid Empire. Yet it would be the Holy Quran that would forever establish his divine support, through the enigmatic story of Dhul-Qarnain: the Two-Horned King."
    },
