    "en": {
     "title": "Who Was Dhul-Qarnain?",
     "blurb": "Cyrus or Alexander? Three clues that identify the Quran's two-horned king.",
     "script": "Who Was Dhul-Qarnain? Here two ancient maps sit side by side: the empire of Alexander the Great, and the Achaemenid Persian Empire around five hundred BCE. Let us set the story in context. The eighteenth chapter of the Holy Quran outlines the evolution of the Christian world; from the righteous and persecuted followers of the Messiah, to great Christian powers falling prey to materialism. This story comes towards its end when it explains how Dhul-Qarnain stopped the entry of the marauding peoples of Gog and Magog from entering his lands. It would be the descendants of Gog and Magog who would become the great European powers of the Latter Days, colonising the world materially and spiritually. But who, then, was Dhul-Qarnain? Most Muslims believe he was Alexander the Great; the Caliphs of the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community, however, have proved that he was Cyrus the Great. Consider three clues. First, the title 'Dhul-Qarnain' means one who possesses two horns, or who spans two generations, two centuries. Cyrus unified two great kingdoms, the Median and the Persian, and his life spanned two generations, while Alexander died at the young age of just thirty-two. Second, the three journeys of Dhul-Qarnain line up with Cyrus's known conquests, which went west, then east; Alexander's conquests spread only east. As the map of Alexander's empire shows, his conquests began in Macedonia, near Greece, and expanded eastwards only, across Asia Minor, the Near East, and through into India and Afghanistan; he never had any westward or northern expansion to his empire. Cyrus, by contrast, rose to kingship in the fortieth year of his life. His first conquest was in five hundred and fifty BCE, of the Medes. He then proceeded westward, conquering Turkey in five hundred and forty-six BCE, before heading east to conquer through to Uzbekistan; and finally, the Quran indicates, he secured his northern border at the Caucasus mountains. And third, Cyrus the Great was a magnificent moral and religious figure, ushering in an unprecedented era of religious freedom. Alexander was a brilliant but profligate pagan conqueror; he cannot be described as the righteous figure of Dhul-Qarnain. The evidence, then, points firmly to Cyrus."
    },
