     "blurb": "The Persian king who freed the exiled Jews and rebuilt Solomon's Temple.",
     "script": "Persian King, Israelite Saviour. This board follows Dhul-Qarnain’s westward journey, and shows how a Persian king became the saviour of the people of Israel. The Holy Quran, chapter eighteen, verse eighty-seven, tells us: “Until, when he reached the setting of the sun, he found it setting in a pool of murky water, and near it he found a people. We said, ‘O Dhu’l Qarnain, either punish them, or treat them with kindness.’” The sun, of course, sets in the west. And it was a king of Western Turkey who attacked Cyrus in five hundred and forty-six BCE. Cyrus marched from his base in Iran and defeated an army twice the size of his own. This region, near today’s Izmir, is famous for its hot mineral springs and muddy pools; even now the ‘mud baths of Turkey’ are a centre of spa tourism, testifying to the Quran’s use of the word ‘ayn hami’ah, which means, in Lane’s lexicon, “a well or a spring or pool foul with black, fetid mud.” It is a vivid vindication of the Quran’s description. Cyrus then turned to Babylon, where the Jews lay in exile, forced to worship idols and robbed of their homeland, Jerusalem. In five hundred and thirty-nine BCE he defeated Babylon’s army at Opis, then took the city in an extraordinary fashion, diverting the River Euphrates away from the city’s water defences so that his men could wade in by night, and the city was conquered without battle. There Cyrus fulfilled the Quranic instruction perfectly, punishing the guilty and showing kindness to others. He punished the Babylonian elite — the Prince Regent Belshazzar was killed on the night of conquest, ending the Chaldean dynasty. He reversed the forced-labour policies the Babylonians had imposed on conquered peoples. He restored the religious temples of all, and decreed the rebuilding of the Temple of Solomon. And he permitted the Israelites to return to Judea and rebuild their communities. Consider the timeline: in five hundred and forty-six BCE Cyrus took Western Turkey; in five hundred and thirty-nine BCE he defeated the Babylonians; and between five hundred and thirty-eight and five hundred and thirty-six BCE, the rebuilding of the Second Temple began. Without Cyrus, the religion of Moses that later came to be known as Judaism would likely not exist today as we know it."
