    "en": {
     "title": "False Claims of Cyrus' Death",
     "blurb": "Did Cyrus die in the east? The Quran and history suggest otherwise.",
     "script": "False Claims of Cyrus’ Death. This board takes up Dhul-Qarnain’s eastward journey, and answers the old claim that Cyrus perished on that eastern front. The Holy Quran, chapter eighteen, verses ninety-one to ninety-two, says: “Until, when he reached the rising of the sun, he found it rising on a people for whom We had made no shelter against it. Thus indeed it was. Verily, We encompassed with Our knowledge all that was with him.” After securing the western border of his empire, Cyrus advanced to the eastern border. There he fought the Massagetae Scythians, a harsh nomadic people who lived in what is today Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan, east of the Caspian Sea, across today’s Kyzylkum–Karakum desert belt. As nomads they were exposed to the unrelenting sun of Central Asia — just as the Quran describes, a people with no shelter against the rising sun. And not only this: Herodotus records that they worshipped the sun too, sacrificing animals to it. The timeline places these events around five hundred and forty-five to five hundred and forty BCE, when Cyrus established Pasargadae as his capital in Fars and then turned his attention eastward; and around five hundred and forty-five to five hundred and thirty-nine BCE, when he conducted sustained campaigns in Central Asia to secure the empire’s northeastern frontier. Now notice the Quran’s enigmatic statement after mentioning this Eastern expedition: that Allah knows fully all things. This hint indicates that some point of contention arises from the eastern journey. And so it is: some accounts claim he died after these battles. The Quran, however, situates Cyrus’ Eastern journey as only the second of three campaigns, indicating that he lived to fight on. The Greek historians give at least three differing accounts of his death. Herodotus, having explicitly chosen the story that best fits his theme of moral hubris, recounts that Cyrus was beheaded in the Eastern expedition by the tribal queen Tomyris, in fulfilment of an oath she had sworn to the sun-god. Ctesias claims Cyrus fought against a group of the Massagetae, was injured, and died later after returning home, in Persia. But Xenophon reports that Cyrus was victorious against the Massagetae and lived out a long, full life, dying years later. The Quran aligns with Xenophon’s account, and continues to narrate his story after his supposed death. And Cyrus’ well-known tomb, the stepped stone monument pictured here, stands at Pasargadae in south-western Iran — over two thousand miles away from the Massagetae — bearing silent witness that he did not die on the eastern front."
    },
