     "blurb": "Salman the Persian's long search for truth, ending at the Prophet's side.",
     "script": "The Persian Companion. Palm trees rise before a mosque here, a fitting image for Salman Al-Farsi, Salman the Persian. Born in Isfahan, in modern-day Iran, Salman was raised as a Magian firekeeper, that is, a Zoroastrian. He once came across a Christian church, and was so impressed by their worship that, upon telling his father of his desire to convert, he was shackled in the house. After escaping to Syria, he travelled the lands, searching for spiritual teachers who adhered to true righteousness. But on his death bed, his last teacher advised that there were none like him left. He did, however, foretell that a new Prophet was coming to the Arabs, and gave Salman three marks of his Prophethood to test him with, saying that he would come to a land between two bare tracts, populated by palm trees. Salman now had his next destination. He found his way to Arabia, but was betrayed and sold into slavery. Eventually he reached Medina, a land of palm trees, and waited. One day, he heard that a man claiming to be a Prophet was coming to Medina. He rushed to see if he fulfilled the three marks: distributing but not accepting charity, eating of a gift, and bearing a particular mark on his back. Upon testing him, he discovered that the Prophet was true; and from then on, Salman would never leave the Prophet in a time of need. Though he had begun his life as a Magian, Salman played a pivotal role in protecting his Muslim brethren from the idolaters. As the Holy Quran teaches, in chapter twenty-two, verse eighteen: \"As to those who believe, and the Jews, and the Sabians, and the Christians, and the Magians and the idolaters, verily, Allah will judge between them on the Day of Resurrection; surely, Allah is Witness over all things.\" When the Muslims were being attacked by a huge army, Salman used his knowledge of non-Arab warfare to suggest digging a protective trench on the exposed side of Medina. This approach, never seen before by the Arabs, worked, and the Muslims were victorious against the idolaters once more. And when two groups of the companions argued as to whether Salman was of the Emigrants, who left Mecca, or of the Helpers, who were from Medina, the Prophet, peace and blessings be upon him, intervened, saying: \"Salman is from among us, that is, the People of the Prophet's Household.\""
