     "script": "Persian Downfall. Before you, a row of carved Persian heads gazes out from Persepolis. The Prophet Muhammad, peace and blessings be upon him, was commissioned to pronounce his Prophethood to the world, and so he wrote letters to both Heraclius and Khoswrow the Second, inviting them to Islam. Heraclius treated both the message and the emissary who brought it with great respect. Khoswrow, however, was incensed when he read the letter, and tore it to pieces, saying: \"He is my servant and he addresses me in this way!\" When the Prophet heard how the message of Allah had been treated, he proclaimed: \"Now these people shall themselves be shattered to pieces.\" His letter to Persia had been a message of peace. It read: \"I write this letter in the name of Allah, the Gracious, who grants the best reward of our deeds. This letter is from Muhammad, the Messenger of Allah addressed to the Ruler of Persia. Peace be on him who accepts the guidance and believes in Allah and His Messenger and bears witness that there is none worthy of worship except God, He has no partner; And also bears witness that Muhammad is His Servant and Messenger. O Ruler of Persia! I invite you to the call of Allah, as I am the messenger of Allah to the whole of mankind; so that I may warn every living person and so that the judgement of God may overtake the disbelievers. O Ruler of Persia! Accept Islam, for this is the only way to your salvation. However, if you turn away, then remember that the sin of your Zoroastrian people shall also be on your shoulders.\" But Khoswrow answered with an assassination. He ordered the Governor of Yemen to send two men to arrest the Holy Prophet: he was to give allegiance to the Persian Emperor, or face death. When the emissaries reached the Prophet and gave their demands, the Holy Prophet asked them to stay the night. In the morning, he told them: \"Tell your master that my Lord, the God of power, has killed his master last night.\" When the emissaries returned to Yemen, they told the Governor the prophecy. And within days they received word: Khoswrow the Second had been murdered by his own son, and the murder had taken place on the very night the prophecy was revealed. Though neither Heraclius nor Khoswrow accepted Islam, one gave respect to the message while the other tore it to pieces. And for this reason, the Prophet said: \"The Persian Kingdom shall be destroyed at once, but God shall grant some respite to the Roman Empire.\" And so it was."
