     "title": "The Persian Messiah",
     "blurb": "The Persian roots of Hazrat Ahmad and his great defence of Islam.",
     "script": "The Persian Messiah. Before you rises an ornate Mughal-style palace facade, a fitting backdrop for the story of a reformer of Persian origin. Consider first the ascent of faith. The Holy Quran, in chapter sixty-two, verse four, declares: \"He it is Who has raised among the Unlettered people a Messenger from among themselves who recites unto them His Signs, and purifies them, and teaches them the Book and wisdom, although they were before, in manifest misguidance. And among others from among them who have not yet joined them. He is the Mighty, the Wise.\" A companion related: \"One Day we were sitting with the Holy Prophet when Surah Jumu'ah was revealed,\" and the Prophet put his hand on Salman the Persian and said, as recorded in Bukhari: \"If Faith were to go up to the Pleiades, a man from these would surely find it.\" Now consider Ahmad the Persian. The family of Hazrat Ahmad, who lived from eighteen thirty-five to nineteen hundred and eight, was of Persian origin. His ancestors settled in a region of modern Uzbekistan called Samarkand, a land that had been ruled by Persian empires and had deeply entrenched Persianate culture. He received many revelations indicating his Persian origin, among them: \"A man of Persian descent has published the refutation of those who have disbelieved and have obstructed people from the path of Allah. Allah appreciates his effort. The book of the friend of Allah is the sword of 'Ali.\" And so we come to the champion of Allah. Born in eighteen thirty-five into a family of local chieftains, Ahmad spent his early life in solitude, studying Islamic, Christian and Hindu scriptures, and sinking deep into prayer. Though he sought to remain unknown, he eventually felt compelled to defend Islam publicly against the many attacks it was enduring. In the eighteen-eighties he released a magnificent defence of Islam entitled Barahin-e-Ahmadiyya. About this work, the cleric who would one day become his bitterest enemy wrote: \"In our opinion, from the point of view of the modern age, this book stands unique in the history of Islam. No book has ever been published like it in the past, and we cannot say anything about the future, which is known only to God. The perseverance of the author in the service of Islam, through his life, his energy, pen, tongue, and every form of activity is almost unprecedented amongst Muslims. This should not be taken as Asiatic exaggeration. We challenge anyone to show us the like of this book.\""
