     "blurb": "The Palace of Chosroes has been shaken: a prophecy of Iran's upheaval.",
     "script": "The Palace Prophecy. On the fifteenth of January, nineteen hundred and six, the Promised Messiah received a striking revelation, later published in Badr on the nineteenth of January that same year: \"The Palace of Chosroes has been shaken.\" This momentous prophecy concerned the modern rulers of Iran, the Qajar Monarchy. Until this revelation, the Qajar monarchy had enjoyed over a century of absolute imperial rule. The Shah had the full military and diplomatic support of Imperial Russia. Muzaffarud-Din Shah, the Shah at the time, had recently accepted some constitutional reforms, and this revelation indicated that a fundamental change in Iranian history was about to take place. Then came the coup. After the Shah's death in nineteen hundred and seven, conflict intensified between his successor, Mohammad Ali Shah, and the Iranian Parliament. In nineteen hundred and eight, the new Shah suspended the constitutional order and had Cossack forces shell the parliament building in Tehran. His crackdown briefly restored royal rule. However, pro-constitutional forces organised armed resistance. In nineteen hundred and nine, they captured Tehran and forced the Shah to abdicate in favour of his young son. The monarchy limped on before ending in nineteen twenty-five. The palace of Chosroes had truly been shaken. Alongside this stood a revelation about the uniting of Muslims. Received on the twentieth of November, nineteen hundred and five, it showed the unifying purpose of his advent: \"Gather together all the Muslims on the face of the earth so that they should unite in one faith.\" And in a Persian revelation of the eleventh of March, nineteen hundred and six, he was told: \"When the reign of the Messiah, the monarch begins, the Muslims who were Muslims in name only will be reconverted to Islam.\" He explained its meaning: \"In this revelation, by the reign of the just monarch is meant the period of the call of this humble one. No worldly kingdom is indicated here, but the kingdom of heaven that has been bestowed upon me. The meaning of this revelation is that when the kingdom of heaven, which in the estimation of Allah is the period of the Promised Messiah, the effect of it was that those who were only Muslims in name began to be Muslims in fact, as has already happened in the case of about four hundred thousand of them.\""
